Pop the @sweetcorn{4} cobettes onto a lined #baking tray{} and drizzle on some
@oil{}.

Season with @salt{} and sprinkle on half the @Mexican Style Spice Mix{1/2}.
Use your hands to rub the flavours all over the corn.

Roast in the #oven{} until soft and golden, ~{15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @Echalion Shallot{1}.

Zest, then halve the @Lime{1}.

Drain and rinse the @Red Kidney Beans{1} in a #sieve{}.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} over medium-high heat.
When hot, add the shallot, stir and cook until softened, ~{3%minutes}.

Add the remaining @Mexican Style Spice Mix{1/2}, @Tomato Puree{15},
@Easy Garlic{1/2}, stir and cook for ~{1%minute}. Stir in the kidney beans
and turn the heat to low.

Cook the @Steamed Basmati Rice{1} according to the pack instructions.
When ready, stir the rice into the kidneys beans, coat in the spice mix and
remove from the heat.

Season the rice with @salt{} and @pepper{} and stir in half each of the lime
zest and juice. Set aside.

Slice lengthways into the @Avocado{1}. Once you reach the stone turn the
avocado around to cut it in half. Twist each half and pull it apart. Remove
the stone then scoop out all of the insides into a #bowl{}.

Add the remaining lime zest and juice. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}
and then use a #fork{} to mash to a smooth paste. Guac done!

Share the rice between your plates and top with the roasted corn.

Serve the guac alongside and finish with a drizzle of @Soured Cream{75}.

> The taste of warm, buttery sweet corn on the cob is hard to beat, especially
> when it's marinated in our special Mexican spice rub. Served with
> Mexican-style beans and rice, creamy homemade guacamole and a drizzle of
> cooling sour cream, this deliciously simple dish is perfect for a
> quick-fix supper.